<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="spatial-accessibility">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>accessibility-specialist</domain>
    <summary>Design XR interfaces accessible to users with disabilities: motor, visual, hearing, vestibular. Multiple inputs (gaze/voice/controller), seated mode, 3D captions, spatial audio per W3C XAUR.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>xr</tag>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
      <tag>spatial</tag>
      <tag>wcag</tag>
      <tag>inclusive-design</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Spatial Accessibility in XR Interfaces</title>

    <summary>Accessibility methodology for spatial/XR interfaces (Apple Vision Pro, Meta Quest, HoloLens, WebXR) addressing motor limitations, visual and hearing impairment, cognitive load, and motion sensitivity. Core requirements: multiple simultaneous input modalities (gaze + voice + controller + hand), seated mode as the default, 3D captions that face the user, spatial audio navigation for blind users, and alignment with W3C XR Accessibility User Requirements (XAUR).</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Traditional WCAG does not fully cover spatial environments. XAUR is a Working Draft, not normative — but it is the current best-practice reference. Screen reader support in XR is fragmented (VoiceOver works for visionOS native UI but not all Unity/WebXR content); eye-tracking dwell requires hardware (Vision Pro yes, Quest 2 no). Without explicit accessibility design, XR excludes wheelchair users (reach zones), blind users (no audio navigation), deaf users (no captions for spatial audio), and users with vestibular disorders (no locomotion alternatives).</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Designing or shipping for Apple Vision Pro, Meta Quest, HoloLens, Android XR, or WebXR.</item>
        <item>Adding accessibility features to an existing XR application pre-release.</item>
        <item>Auditing an immersive product against W3C XAUR.</item>
        <item>Enterprise XR (training, digital twins, remote assist) where ADA Title II or EAA may apply.</item>
        <item>Adding alternative input modalities to a single-modality XR experience.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>2D web/mobile a11y — use `a11y-testing` and WCAG 2.2 AA.</item>
        <item>Game-only experiences where motion is core gameplay — apply selectively to menus and settings only.</item>
        <item>Internal R&amp;D prototypes never seen by real users.</item>
        <item>Where the platform's built-in a11y settings fully address user needs without custom work.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="multiple-input-modalities">
      <rule>
        <statement>Provide all input modalities simultaneously (gaze + voice + controller + hand gesture) — never require users to switch modality mid-task, and never make any single modality the only path to complete an action.</statement>
        <rationale>W3C XAUR requires multiple input alternatives. Gaze requires eye-tracking hardware (Vision Pro yes; Quest 2 no); voice degrades in noisy environments; controller excludes users with limited arm mobility. Only providing all options simultaneously guarantees coverage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Input Modality Matrix">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Interaction   | Touch/Controller  | Voice              | Gaze+Dwell
Select object | Tap / trigger     | "Select [name]"    | Look for 1.5s
Move object   | Drag / joystick   | "Move to [loc]"    | Dwell + direction
Open menu     | Button press      | "Show menu"        | Look at menu icon
Cancel        | B button / back   | "Cancel"           | Look away
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <section name="gaze-input">
        <list>
          <item>Dwell time: 1-2 seconds; show visual countdown ring on gaze target.</item>
          <item>Confirmation before any irreversible action — cancel by looking away.</item>
          <item>Gaze requires eye-tracking hardware; check platform capability at runtime before enabling.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="voice-control">
        <rule>
          <statement>Every spatial interaction must have a named voice-command alternative; publish a visible command list in-world.</statement>
          <rationale>Voice commands must be discoverable; if users cannot find the command vocabulary, voice is not actually an accessible path. On-device ASR keeps response latency under 500ms — cloud LLM calls violate this threshold.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>Voice command response must feel &lt;500ms — use on-device ASR, not cloud LLM round-trip.</item>
          <item>Provide error recovery: "I didn't understand. Say 'Help' to see available commands."</item>
          <item>Test with diverse accents; generated grammars miss accent variants.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="head-tracking">
        <list>
          <item>Nod to confirm, shake to cancel, tilt to scroll — always provide a voice or controller alternative.</item>
          <item>Limit head-tracking interactions: neck strain risk with sustained use.</item>
          <item>Allow sensitivity adjustment in accessibility settings.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="visual-accessibility">
      <section name="blind-users-spatial-audio-navigation">
        <rule>
          <statement>Attach directional audio beacons to spatial landmarks (entrance, exit, key interactive objects) with distinct timbres so blind users can navigate by sound.</statement>
          <rationale>Without spatial audio wayfinding, blind users have no equivalent to visual scanning. Distinct timbres per object type allow users to build a mental map of the environment.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>Directional audio cues: volume indicates distance, stereo panning indicates direction.</item>
          <item>AI-powered object descriptions: announce objects in view, describe spatial relationships, read text encountered, warn of obstacles.</item>
          <item>Haptic feedback: vibration for object proximity, different patterns for object types.</item>
          <item>Screen reader integration (where platform supports it): announce spatial UI elements, navigate menus with voice.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="low-vision-users">
        <list>
          <item>High contrast mode in 3D space — adjustable contrast for AR/VR overlays.</item>
          <item>Large text in spatial UI — adjustable size and distance from user.</item>
          <item>Color-blind safe palettes for all spatial indicators.</item>
          <item>Edge highlighting for interactive objects.</item>
          <item>Zoom functionality within the XR environment.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="seated-mode">
      <rule>
        <statement>Default to seated mode and teleportation-only locomotion; promote standing and smooth locomotion as opt-in settings, not the other way around.</statement>
        <rationale>Wheelchair users, users with limited mobility, and vestibular-sensitive users are excluded by default room-scale and smooth-locomotion experiences. Opt-in seated mode signals they are an afterthought; opt-in standing mode does not.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Seated Mode Implementation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Seated mode adjustments:
  - Lower UI elements to eye level when seated (~1.2m from floor)
  - Closer interaction distances (arm's length from seated position)
  - Reduce vertical range: height -30 to +20 degrees from eye level
  - All controls within horizontal reach zone (+-90 degrees from center)

Locomotion defaults:
  - Teleportation-only (point and click to move)
  - No room-scale movement required
  - No standing up, overhead reaches, or floor interactions
  - Virtual joystick and voice commands as alternatives
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <list>
        <item>Never require room-scale movement, standing, reaching above 1.8m or below 0.5m, or 360-degree rotation.</item>
        <item>Snap-turn default: 30 degrees per step; adjustable from 15 to 90 degrees.</item>
        <item>Seated-mode preset values are platform-specific — do not transfer Vision Pro values directly to Quest 3 or HoloLens.</item>
      </list>
      <reference path="templates/xr-scene-audit.py">Python script auditing scene manifest for seated compatibility and other XAUR requirements</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="hearing-accessibility">
      <rule>
        <statement>3D captions must always face the user, include speaker identification, note sound direction (e.g., "[footsteps, behind-left]"), maintain a constant ~1.5m distance, and have a clear background.</statement>
        <rationale>Static caption placement in XR fails as users turn their heads. Caption text that reads "footsteps" without direction information provides no spatial context to deaf users.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Captions at constant ~1.5m distance from user, always facing camera (billboard render mode).</item>
        <item>Include: speech content, speaker identification, significant non-speech sounds, directional cues.</item>
        <item>Adjustable caption size and position in user settings.</item>
        <item>Haptic feedback for important sounds: vibration intensity matches volume, patterns distinguish sound types.</item>
        <item>Visual flash indicators for alerts and alarms (non-flicker: max 3 flashes per second).</item>
        <item>Leverage platform captions first: visionOS 2+ Live Captions, Meta Horizon OS Live Captions.</item>
      </list>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding focus highlight animations for accessibility without checking for flicker/strobe risk.</description>
        <reason>More than 3 flashes per second can trigger photosensitive seizures. All animated focus highlights must be checked against the 3-flash threshold.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="cognitive-load-and-comfort">
      <list>
        <item>Simplified UI mode: hide non-essential elements on demand.</item>
        <item>Consistent button placement and gesture vocabulary across scenes.</item>
        <item>Tutorial reminders and on-screen hints available on demand.</item>
        <item>No time pressure in any core interaction path.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Add vignette during all locomotion and expose a user-adjustable intensity slider; never remove motion sickness mitigations to "improve immersion".</statement>
        <rationale>Vestibular disorders affect ~35% of adults over 40. Smooth locomotion without vignette is a leading cause of simulator sickness that ends XR sessions. Always opt-out, never opt-in for comfort mitigations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Motion sickness: teleportation default; vignette on movement; fixed reference frame available; adjustable movement speed.</item>
        <item>Visual comfort: brightness and contrast adjustment; reduced particle effects option; field-of-view adjustment; disable motion blur.</item>
        <item>Break reminders: suggest break every 20-30 minutes; health and safety warnings on launch; fatigue warnings after sustained use.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Agents help with: a11y settings menu generation, captions placement logic, comfort-setting presets, voice-command vocabulary expansion, content audit against XAUR checklist, alt-text/object-description generation for visible 3D objects. Agents cannot: validate motion-sickness comfort, assess haptic feedback strength, run real-user testing. Pipeline: scene-graph audit (find interactive objects without alt-description, missing voice commands, no seated-mode equivalent) → settings-menu generator → human XR tester validates per device.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Recommended subagents: `faion-sdd-executor-agent` — track each XAUR criterion as a task; require platform-specific evidence (visionOS, Quest, HoloLens).</item>
        <item>Scene-audit subagent — given Unity/Unreal/visionOS scene description, list interactive entities and verify each has voice + gaze + controller path.</item>
        <item>Object-description generator — given object metadata (type, position, label) emit screen-reader announcement and 3D caption text.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Provide ALL inputs simultaneously (gaze + voice + controller + hand) — do not require user to switch modality mid-task.</item>
        <item>Default to seated mode and teleport-only locomotion; promote standing/smooth as opt-ins.</item>
        <item>3D captions should follow the user (face camera), include speaker direction indicator, sit at constant ~1.5m distance.</item>
        <item>For blind users, attach spatial-audio beacons to landmarks (entrance, exit, key NPCs) with distinct timbres.</item>
        <item>Use vignette during locomotion; expose user-adjustable intensity slider.</item>
        <item>Limit head-tracking interactions (nod/shake) — neck strain risk; always offer voice/controller alternative.</item>
        <item>Align with platform a11y APIs first (visionOS Voice Control, Quest captions); build custom only when needed.</item>
        <item>Test with at least 3 user groups: wheelchair user (seated mode), low-vision user (UI scale, contrast), motion-sensitive user (comfort settings).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLM-generated 3D-object descriptions hallucinate visual details; clamp to known metadata only or feed vision-model output explicitly.</item>
        <item>Voice command grammars produced by an agent often miss accent variants — see `vui-accessibility-inclusivity`; require diverse voice testing.</item>
        <item>Auto-generated captions from spatial audio drop directional info; the agent must add "[behind-left]" / "[in front]" tags from scene metadata, not from audio alone.</item>
        <item>Agent loops that "fix XR a11y" can introduce flicker/strobe by adding focus highlights — must respect 3-flashes-per-second rule.</item>
        <item>Watch for FOV bugs: putting captions in default visionOS 60° optical center may not reach Quest's wider FOV; agent must adjust per platform.</item>
        <item>Seated-mode preset values from one platform DON'T transfer; agent must keep per-platform tables (Vision Pro vs. Quest 3 vs. HoloLens).</item>
        <item>Don't let agent recommend "remove all motion" by default — some vestibular-OK users prefer smooth locomotion. Always opt-out, not forced.</item>
        <item>Latency requirements differ: voice-command response must feel less than 500 ms; agent's cloud LLM call can violate that — prefer on-device ASR.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <list>
        <item>WCAG 2.2 doesn't fully cover spatial — XAUR is a Working Draft, not normative; many recommendations are still emerging.</item>
        <item>Screen reader support in XR is fragmented: VoiceOver on visionOS works for native UI but not all WebXR or Unity content.</item>
        <item>Eye-tracking dwell selection requires hardware (Vision Pro yes, Quest 2 no, Quest Pro/3 limited).</item>
        <item>Voice control quality drops in noisy environments and for diverse accents (see `vui-accessibility-inclusivity`).</item>
        <item>Spatial audio + haptics specs vary per platform — no single "alt text" for 3D objects yet.</item>
        <item>Real testing requires diverse user panels with XR experience; rare and expensive to recruit.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/xr-scene-audit.py" purpose="Python script auditing a scene manifest JSON for missing voice alias, gaze support, controller mapping, accessible description, and seated compatibility."/>
    </templates>

